  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="25" relname="span">I think P22 is exactly right here.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="15" relname="conjunction"> 
I&apos;ve been using computer since the early DOS days </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="15" relname="conjunction">
and have seen many different application design styles, </segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="7" relname="span">
so certain things may seem more intuitive to me </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="16" relname="disjunction">
because I have encountered similar things in the past </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="16" relname="disjunction">
or I may be better at jumping to certain conclusions.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="18" relname="span"> 
However, for newer users, the number of design philosophies that are truly intuitive to them is considerably smaller.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="22" relname="span"> 

Intuitiveness is only relavent as a application description</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="17" relname="span">
 if it used with the right context.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="19" relname="span"> 
Without appropriate contextualization, the term is meaningless</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="5" relname="concession">
 (other than, as P22 points out, a good marketing tool).</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="21" relname="conjunction"> 
Because every person is different</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="21" relname="conjunction"> and just about every application is different, </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="23" relname="span">
intuitiveness as design measure becomes incalculable and therefore worthless. 

</segment>
